        _vm._v(" "),
        _c("li", [_vm._v("Bill of Materials")]),
        _vm._v(" "),
        _c("li", [_vm._v("Tracking Additional Cost of Manufacturing")]),
        _vm._v(" "),
        _c("li", [_vm._v("Job Costing")]),
        _vm._v(" "),
        _c("li", [_vm._v("Stock Ageing Analysis")]),
        _vm._v(" "),
        _c("li", [_vm._v("Batch Related Stock Ageing")]),
        _vm._v(" "),
        _c("li", [_vm._v("Price List with Multi Price levels")]),
        _vm._v(" "),
        _c("li", [_vm._v("Reorder Levels")]),
        _vm._v(" "),
        _c("li", [
          _vm._v("Movement Analysis (Partywise/ Itemwise/ Stock Groupwise)"),
        ]),
        _vm._v(" "),
        _c("li", [
          _vm._v(
            "Profitability Analysis (Stock Groupwise / Stock Itemwise / Invoicewise / Locationwise)"
          ),
        ]),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("h2", { attrs: { id: "stock-query" } }, [
        _c(
          "a",
          { staticClass: "header-anchor", attrs: { href: "#stock-query" } },
          [_vm._v("#")]
        ),
        _vm._v(" Stock Query"),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "Stock query offers an option for the user to get a good idea of what is the stock position of a par-\nticular item as well as items that belong to the same category or group. The stock query report\ndisplays not only the item but also items within the same category or group. It displays the Stock\nItem details such as closing stock quantities and value and also in which Godown it is available,\nstandard selling price, Last purchase and sale quantity and prices, batch details. The user can\nconfigure the screen to show remarks also."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("h2", { attrs: { id: "multiple-warehouses-locations" } }, [
        _c(
          "a",
          {
            staticClass: "header-anchor",
            attrs: { href: "#multiple-warehouses-locations" },
          },
          [_vm._v("#")]
        ),
        _vm._v(" Multiple Warehouses / Locations"),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "A Warehouse/Godown is a place where stocks/materials are stored. It could be either locations or\neven Storage racks. Your company could be maintaining multiple warehouses/godowns and\nhence would require stock statements for the individual warehouses. Akaunt offers you the\ncapability of maintaining multiple Godowns/Locations (Warehouses). It allows you to create\nmultiple Godowns (warehouses) and at the time of accounting an inventory transaction (sales,\npurchase, stock Journal etc), you can specify Godowns for stock items to be stored or des-\npatched."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "For Example., if you enter a purchase transaction, you will have to specify the Godown where the\nitem will be stored and in the similar manner while entering a sales transaction, you will have to\nspecify the godown from where the goods are issued. Akaunt also allows you to transfer\nmaterials from one godown to another. You can view stock reports for a godown or compare a\ngodown with another and also get a consolidated stock report."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "You can also create godowns to keep track of items issued for job works / Sub-contracts and\nrecord the items issued to and received from job works. Each Job Work / Sub-Contract is treated\nas a godown. You can also track the third party stocks viz., details of stocks sent, consumed and\nbalance lying with the Job Work Godown."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("h2", { attrs: { id: "sub-godowns" } }, [
        _c(
          "a",
          { staticClass: "header-anchor", attrs: { href: "#sub-godowns" } },
          [_vm._v("#")]
        ),
        _vm._v(" Sub-Godowns"),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "Using Akaunt, you can create Sub-Godowns (multiple levels of Godowns). While creating\nsub-Godowns you have to specify name and the parent Godown under which it has to be created.\nAkaunt also allows you to create Virtual Godowns. Virtual Godowns do not allow storage of\nmaterials. They are useful when a city has more than one warehouse Godowns, e.g. in a city\nwhere you have 2 warehouses you can have Godown such as Jayanagar or Indiranagar and\nBangalore being the city is setup as Godown where Allow Storage of Material is set to No. In\nthis case, Bangalore is a virtual godown, logically as it does not exist, but still you can generate a\nstock statement for Bangalore godown."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("h2", { attrs: { id: "stock-transfers-to-godowns" } }, [
        _c(
          "a",
          {
            staticClass: "header-anchor",
            attrs: { href: "#stock-transfers-to-godowns" },
          },
          [_vm._v("#")]
        ),
        _vm._v(" Stock transfers to Godowns"),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "Akaunt allows you to transfer materials from one Godown to another. The transfer of\nmaterials is done using Stock Journals. Akaunt also provides you the facility to create\nvoucher class, which help in simplifying the transfer of materials between godowns."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("h2", { attrs: { id: "multiple-stock-valuation" } }, [
        _c(
          "a",
          {
            staticClass: "header-anchor",
            attrs: { href: "#multiple-stock-valuation" },
          },
          [_vm._v("#")]
        ),
        _vm._v(" Multiple Stock Valuation"),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "In Akaunt, you can evaluate the value of inventories using multiple Stock Valuation methods\nviz., Average Cost, Average price, Last Purchase cost, Last Sales price, FIFO etc. Akaunt\noffers you the flexibility to have different stock valuation methods for every item or the entire stock\nof the company which is valued based on the specific type of costing method, chosen at the time\nof reporting. The user is allowed to view different methods of stock valuations in multiple columns."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("h2", { attrs: { id: "batch-wise-lot-wise-expiry-date-handling" } }, [
        _c(
          "a",
          {
            staticClass: "header-anchor",
            attrs: { href: "#batch-wise-lot-wise-expiry-date-handling" },
          },
          [_vm._v("#")]
        ),
        _vm._v(" Batch-wise / Lot-wise & Expiry Date Handling"),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "Akaunt allows you to specify the Batch/Lot details for stock items in order to identify and track\nthe required inventory, as and when required for any kind of reference/verification/sale/query and\nso on. it also allows you to specify the expiry dates and manufacturing dates for stock items. This\nfeature is extremely useful in Pharmaceutical, Chemical, Food and other industries which deal in\nperishable / life saving items. Additionally, you can ensure that expiry date items are not available\nfor invoicing."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("h2", { attrs: { id: "sales-and-purchase-order-processing" } }, [
        _c(
          "a",
          {
            staticClass: "header-anchor",
            attrs: { href: "#sales-and-purchase-order-processing" },
          },
          [_vm._v("#")]
        ),
        _vm._v(" Sales and Purchase Order Processing"),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "Akaunt facilitates Order processing right from placing the order for supply of materials and\nreceiving an order from the customers. It provides all the required vouchers, features and options\nto process Purchase Orders as well as Sales Orders. Using the Order Processing functionality of\nAkaunt, you can also generate reports for outstanding purchase and sales orders. You may\nalso e-mail the PO to suppliers from within Akaunt using e-mail option."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("h2", { attrs: { id: "tracking-inventory" } }, [
        _c(
          "a",
          {
            staticClass: "header-anchor",
            attrs: { href: "#tracking-inventory" },
          },
          [_vm._v("#")]
        ),
        _vm._v(" Tracking Inventory"),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "Generally, Invoices are sent along with the goods sold. However, there are certain instances,\nwhere the goods are despatched first and then the invoices are sent later or vice versa. In such\ncases, the stocks balances are not updated simulnateously with the books of accounts. Akaunt\n9 provides facility to use tracking numbers, wherein you can enter Receipt Note and Delivery\nNotes with tracking numbers and track the receipt and despatch of goods.\nAlthough these vouchers do not affect your accounts they are displayed in the Profit and Loss A/c\nunder the heading Purchase Bills to Come under Purchase Accounts and Sales Bills to Make\nunder Sales Accounts."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("h2", { attrs: { id: "rejection-in-and-rejection-out" } }, [
        _c(
          "a",
          {
            staticClass: "header-anchor",
            attrs: { href: "#rejection-in-and-rejection-out" },
          },
          [_vm._v("#")]
        ),
        _vm._v(" Rejection In and Rejection Out"),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "Materials that you purchase or sell might be returned due to damages or other reasons. Akaunt\n9 handles rejections from the customers or to the supplier with the help of Rejections In (Sales\nreturns) and Rejections Out (Purchase returns) Vouchers. These rejection entries update only\nthe inventory books.\nBut in some cases, you would like to scrap those materials which are Rejected In (i.e. Sales\nreturns), in such cases you can activate Treat all Rejection Inwards as Scrap to Yes, during\nstock item creation / Alteration screen."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("h2", { attrs: { id: "additional-costs-incurred-on-purchase" } }, [
        _c(
          "a",
          {
            staticClass: "header-anchor",
            attrs: { href: "#additional-costs-incurred-on-purchase" },
          },
          [_vm._v("#")]
        ),
        _vm._v(" Additional Costs Incurred on Purchase"),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "When you make a purchase, you may incur additional expenses like freight, handling charges,\ntaxes and so on. This cost is also referred to as Landed Cost, Akaunt allows you to add\nthese costs to the value of the product during voucher entry or later. These expenses are\nsometimes included in the Supplier Invoice or directly borne by the buyer, in such cases you have\nto book these expenses in order to ascertain the landed cost of the product and ultimately which\nwill help in determining the Item pricing and your margin. In Akaunt, you may book additional\ncost incurred on purchases in two ways :"
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("h2", { attrs: { id: "unlimited-stock-item-classification" } }, [
        _c(
          "a",
          {
            staticClass: "header-anchor",
            attrs: { href: "#unlimited-stock-item-classification" },
          },
          [_vm._v("#")]
        ),
        _vm._v(" Unlimited Stock Item Classification"),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "Akaunt provides the flexibility to maintain unlimited stock item classification for your invento-\nries. depending upon your nature of business / needs. If you are a manufacturing concern, you\nmay primarily require three broad classfiications of the Stocks Groups i.e., Raw Materials, Work-\nin-Progress & Finished Goods.\nDepending upon the nature of business, you may create any number stock groups and classify\nstock items under them at point of time. When Integrate Accounts with Inventory is enabled,\nthe closing values of inventories under each of the stock groups are automatically reported in the\nfinancial statements. However, If you have not opted to Integrate Accounts with Inventory, you\ncan created Ledgers as Raw Materials, Work-in-Progress and Finished Goods Stock-in-Hand\ngroup and generate balance sheet as of a particular date."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("h2", { attrs: { id: "bill-of-materials" } }, [
        _c(
          "a",
          {
            staticClass: "header-anchor",
            attrs: { href: "#bill-of-materials" },
          },
          [_vm._v("#")]
        ),
        _vm._v(" Bill of Materials"),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "In many segments of the industries, especially in Manufacturing/Assembling organisations, there\nare number of components/inputs/spares that go into the manufacturing/assembling of finished\nGoods. Each process of manufacturing of raw materials to finished goods / intermediate goods\ncomprises of a List of components known as Bill of Materials (BoM) containing the list of com-\nponents involved in the manufacturing/assembling of the finished goods. In Akaunt, you can\ncreate a bill of materials and specify the list of items (alongwith the Godown and Quantity details)\nthat are required for manufacturing the finished / intermediate product.\nOnce, the Bill of materails is created, you can use Manufacturing Journal and specify the quantity\nof finished goods that are to be manufactured. Akaunt, immediately selects all items required\nto manufacture the finished product and automatically adjusts (decreases) the stocks. You can\nalso enter additional costs like wages, power, water charges etc, to the cost of the items used in\nmanufacturing."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("h2", { attrs: { id: "tracking-additional-cost-of-manufacturing" } }, [
        _c(
          "a",
          {
            staticClass: "header-anchor",
            attrs: { href: "#tracking-additional-cost-of-manufacturing" },
          },
          [_vm._v("#")]
        ),
        _vm._v(" Tracking Additional Cost of Manufacturing"),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "When you manufacture a product, you have to consider certain other costs like water charges,\nwages and electricity in addition to the cost of the component, which are added to the product\ncost during the process of manufacturing. In Akaunt , you can record additional costs in % or\nas notional value to the product cost, while entering a manufacturing Journal.\nTo track Additional Costs of manufacturing, create a Manufacturing Journal with BoM in the\nmanner, as explained in the previous section."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("h2", { attrs: { id: "job-costing" } }, [
        _c(
          "a",
          { staticClass: "header-anchor", attrs: { href: "#job-costing" } },
          [_vm._v("#")]
        ),
        _vm._v(" Job Costing"),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "Akaunt facilitates tracking of cost and revenue information down to the smallest detail for any\nJob Work/contract undertaken or outsourced to third parties. In order to ascertain the actual costs\nincurred for each job, each job is assigned a job number or Job name and then Job costing\nsystems accumulate costs separately for each product or service, based on the jobs/tasks under-\ntaken or materials consumed, for each such product or service. In Akaunt each Jobwork /\nsub-contract is created as Godown and Cost Centres are deployed to accumulate Cost /\nrevenue for each job.\nYou can use Stock Journals to transfer materials from your company's godown(s) to job workers /\nsub-contractors location and track the consumption of goods sent for processing. This helps to\nkeep track of the materials issued and consumed at the job work units. Additionaly, you can also\naccount for costs incurred using purchase / payments / journal vouchers."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("h2", { attrs: { id: "stock-ageing-analysis" } }, [
        _c(
          "a",
          {
            staticClass: "header-anchor",
            attrs: { href: "#stock-ageing-analysis" },
          },
          [_vm._v("#")]
        ),
        _vm._v(" Stock Ageing Analysis"),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "The Stock Ageing Analysis report is significant report, which is very useful to you to know, how\nfast the inventory of various stock items is moving. This allows your management to decide the\nproduction plan and its schedule. The report by default shows you the ageing period for each and\nevery stock item, by date of purchase. However, you can select the style of ageing, by selecting\nthe option Ageing Style (i.e. By date of Purchase, By Mfg date, By Expiry Date, To be expired).\nYou can also change the period of ageing, by selecting the F6 option. Akaunt provides you\nflexibility to specify combination of expiry date and ageing for monitoring goods of perishable\nnature / pharmaceutical industry."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("h2", { attrs: { id: "batch-related-stock-ageing-report" } }, [
        _c(
          "a",
          {
            staticClass: "header-anchor",
            attrs: { href: "#batch-related-stock-ageing-report" },
          },
          [_vm._v("#")]
        ),
        _vm._v(" Batch Related Stock Ageing Report"),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "Akaunt has a facility to generate batch related stock reporting. If you look at the ageing\nanalysis you can view items with their batches references, dates of Mfg and Expiry dates.\nYou can also get a report on those items whose shelf-lives have expired or likely to expire. You\ncan move those fast by offering discounts or returning to the manufacturers (as in the case of food\nand medicine stocks). You can also view ageing reports for all batches."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("h2", { attrs: { id: "price-list-with-multi-price-levels" } }, [
        _c(
          "a",
          {
            staticClass: "header-anchor",
            attrs: { href: "#price-list-with-multi-price-levels" },
          },
          [_vm._v("#")]
        ),
        _vm._v(" Price List with Multi Price levels"),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "Akaunt allows you to predefine multiple levels of price lists. For e.g. you can define price lists\nfor Distributors, Dealers and Retailers. While defining the price lists Akaunt displays the cost\nprice as well as last price (historical data) for that particular stock item. This simplifies and\nexpedites invoicing and also eliminates the possibilities of errors at the time of Invoice entry.\nYou can predefine price levels for parties at the time of their ledger accounts creation. When you\nselect a particular party during entry, you have to select only the stock items and enter the qty.\nThe related price is prefilled automatically based on the levels defined."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("h2", { attrs: { id: "reorder-levels" } }, [
        _c(
          "a",
          { staticClass: "header-anchor", attrs: { href: "#reorder-levels" } },
          [_vm._v("#")]
        ),
        _vm._v(" Reorder Levels"),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "It is essential for your company to maintain sufficient inventory levels to cater to the growing\nneeds of your customers and smoothly run your business. In order to have adequate stocks, you\nhave to maintain information in respect of consumption pattern and reorder levels."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "Akaunt provides you facility to maintain reorder level details for each stock item. You can\ndefine reorder levels as well as minimum order quantity for stock items based on the consumption\npattern and as per requirements for a specific period (i.e. Days, Months, Weeks, and Years).\nAkaunt also provides you information on stock items whose balances have gone below\nspecified reorder levels."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c(
        "h2",
        {
          attrs: { id: "movement-analysis-partywise-itemwise-stock-groupwise" },
        },
        [
          _c(
            "a",
            {
              staticClass: "header-anchor",
              attrs: {
                href: "#movement-analysis-partywise-itemwise-stock-groupwise",
              },
            },
            [_vm._v("#")]
          ),
          _vm._v(" Movement Analysis (Partywise/ Itemwise/ Stock Groupwise)"),
        ]
      ),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "Akaunt offers you yet another important inventory management tool called Movement\nAnalysis. With this report you can analyse the movement pattern of materials either party wise,\ngroup wise or item wise. Using this report you can analyse the price at which each supplier has\nsupplied a particular item.\nMovement Analysis of a stock group shows the total inward and outward movement of stock items\nwith their effective rates and values for that particular group. The Movement Analysis for a party\nshows the inward and outward movements of all stocks with effective rate and value. Select an\nitem to drill down further and Akaunt displays transaction wise details along with a separate\ncolumn for additional cost."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c(
        "h2",
        {
          attrs: {
            id: "profitability-analysis-stock-groupwise-stock-itemwise-invoicewise-locationwise",
          },
        },
        [
          _c(
            "a",
            {
              staticClass: "header-anchor",
              attrs: {
                href: "#profitability-analysis-stock-groupwise-stock-itemwise-invoicewise-locationwise",
              },
            },
            [_vm._v("#")]
          ),
          _vm._v(
            " Profitability Analysis (Stock Groupwise / Stock Itemwise / Invoicewise / Locationwise)"
          ),
        ]
      ),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "Using Akaunt, you can automatically calculate the gross profit for an item based on its sale\nprice and consumption cost. Gross profit is the difference the between sale price and the con-\nsumption value. The consumption value is calculated based on the purchase price. You can\ncalculate gross profits for each invoice, stock item, stock group as well as items and location wise."
        ),
      ]),
    ]
  )
}
var staticRenderFns = []
render._withStripped = true

export { render, staticRenderFns }
